        "text": "Home/\n\nIAS/\n\nArticle\n\nAlvars and Nayanars – Difference Between Alvars and Nayanars\n\nBy BYJU'S Exam Prep\n\nUpdated on: November 14th, 2023\n\nThe major difference between Alvars and Nayanars of Tamil Nadu was their devoted gods. The Nayanars poet-saints were devoted to Lord Shiva, while the Alvars were the devotees of Lord Vishnu or Lord Krishna (an avatar of Lord Vishnu). The Nayanars saints lived from the 6th to the 8th century, and the Alvar poet saints existed from the 7th to the 10th century. Some of the vital intellectuals of Alvars are Sri Andal, Thiruppan Alvar, etc., and some of the crucial intellectuals of Nayanars are Tiru Neelakanta, Viralminda, etc.\n\nDifference Between Alvars and Nayanars PDF\n\nAlvars and Nayanars differ in the way that the Alvars were devotees of Vishnu, while the leaders of the Nayanars were Shiva worshipers. The Nayanars and Alvars ushered one of the biggest religious movements in Southern India from the 7th to the 10th century. It was known as the Bhakti movement. Below, in this article, you will learn about the key differences between Alvars and Nayanars.\n\nTable of content\n\n1. Difference Between Alvars and Nayanars\n\n2. Alvars and Nayanars\n\n3. Who were Alvars?\n\n4. Who were Nayanars?\n\n5. Key Difference Between Alvars and Nayanars\n\nDifference Between Alvars and Nayanars\n\nAlvars and Nayanars were Hindu poet-saints from the south. Apart from this similarity, below are the major difference between Alvars and Nayanars listed in the table. Regional languages like Tamil, Kannada, Bengali, Hindi, Marathi, and others expanded due to the movement, and the lower classes rose to prominence.\n\nThe movement also placed equal attention on men and women while highlighting the significance of women in society.\n\nAlvars and Nayanars\n\nAlvars and Nayanars have been an important part of Indian history. These poet-saints were responsible for bringing in the bhakti movement during the 7th century to the 10th century, not only in the southern parts but also in other parts of India.\n\nSome of the earliest bhakti movements were launched by the Nayanars and the Alvars in the sixth century.\n\nHistorians have always been interested in the difference between Alvars and Nayanars.\n\nThey have noted the names of 12 Alvar saints and 63 Nayanar saints in the historical records.\n\nNambiyandar Nambi, Raja Raja Chola I’s head priest, transformed the songs into a series of booklets known as Tirumurai, while the Alvars’ hymns were collected into Divya Prabandha, a single volume that contained all of their hymns.\n\nWho were Alvars?\n\nThe Alvars was a term used for a group of mystics (12 Tamil Poet Saints) from South India who sang joyous songs in praise of the Hindu God Vishnu. They existed from the 7th to the 10th century and sang from temple to temple.\n\nHistorical records describe the Alvars as falling unconscious while singing rapturously before the image of Lord Vishnu.\n\nThe Alvars sang songs of longing, ecstasy, and service to express their devotion to the gods.\n\nThey existed from the fifth to the tenth centuries CE.\n\nModern scholars believe the Alvars lived between the sixth and eighth centuries AD.\n\nThe Bhakti Movement has revived in the medieval era in part thanks to the Alvars’ acts of devotion.\n\nWith the help of their hymns of devotion to Lord Vishnu and Lord Krishna, they brought the bhakti movement back to life.\n\nWho were Nayanars?\n\nThe Nayanars were 63 Tamil Hindu Saints from the 7th and 8th centuries who were devotees of the Hindu God Shiva and composed devotional poems or hymns in his honor, praising his great beauty.\n\nOne of the characteristics of the Nayanars and the Alvars was that they wandered from place to place and sang beautifully composed poems in honour of the deities.\n\nThe Bhakti movement, which had its beginnings in South India, is also attributed to them.\n\nSundarar is thought to have compiled the Nayanars’ names initially.\n\nBetween the sixth and the eighth centuries CE, they existed.\n\nConclusion:\n\nKey Difference Between Alvars and Nayanars\n\nThe key difference between Alvars and Nayanars is that Alvars worshipped and were devoted to Vishnu, while Nayanars worshipped and were devoted to the all-powerful Shiva and his avatars, including Lord Krishna. The Alvars are thought to have existed between the 5th and 10th centuries AD, while the Nayanars are thought to have lived between 4200 and 2700 BC.\n\nRelated Articles Republican vs Democrat Difference Between Asian and African Elephant Surcharge and Cess Difference Between Creamy and Non Creamy Layer Difference Between Advancing Monsoon and Retreating Monsoon Difference Between Mythology and History Paris Agreement and Kyoto Protocol Difference Between Padma Bhushan and Padma Vibhushan\n\nFAQs on Difference Between Alvars and Nayanars\n\nThe difference between Alvars and Nayanars poet-saints is that Alvars were devoted to Lord Vishnu and his avatars, and Nayanars were devoted to Lord Shiva and his avatars, Lord Krishna.\n\nAlvars and Nayanare were the Hindu poet-saints from the south. The Alvars were the devotees of Lord Vishnu and his avatars who sang rapturously before Lord Vishnu’s ideal. Similar to this, the Nayanars were the devotees of Lord Shiva who composed plenty of devotional poems praising his beauty and avatars.\n\nNayanars belonged to distinct caste backgrounds, such as Brahmanas, commanders, hunters, peasants, potters, untouchable workers, and warriors. The best-known among them were Appar, Manikkavasagar, Sambandar, and Sundarar.\n\nBased on their teachings, the difference between Alvars and Nayanars is that both the Alvars and the Nayanars were devotional saints that sang beautifully-composed poems from temple to temple in honour of their respective deities; the Alvars sang about Vishnu. In contrast, the Nayanars were devotees of Shiva.\n\nRecent Posts\n\nPrime Minister of India: List, Prime Minister and Council of Ministers